text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Discrimination in Tests and Language Learning Tools%0a:Author: rajeev_g%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 30.04.2021 - 22:26%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-191645-785830#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:16-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-191645-785830#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI discuss linguistic discrimination in tests for English language proficiency as well as in language learning apps for English.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aPronunciations of English words vary significantly across different dialects across the US and across the world. However, far too often, language tests like the IELTS and language learning frameworks like Duolingo require one correct pronunciation. This pronunciation tends to be associated with prestige dialects, and results in those who speak different dialects being assessed poorly or told to speak in another way.%0a%0aIELTS and DuoLingo have provided a grant to Okim Kang, who is studying how to make tests and learning frameworks more fair. She argues that "non-native speakers of English or speakers with accents cannot be marginalized just because they have an accent." [1]%0a%0aThe specific linguistic features that are at the root of this discrimination are not mentioned, but the article opens by mentioning the pronunciation of the word "pecan." Even with American dialects, there are four distinct pronunciations: [piːˈkaːn], [pɪˈkaːn], [ˈpɪːkæn], and [ˈpiːkaːn].%0a%0aOn a personal note, I know that my father, who has actually published an (Indian) English book, was faulted on his speaking exam when applying to become a doctor in the US for putting the "wrong" stress on words like "inundated." Not only is the prescriptive nature of this test troubling, it seems curious why it would be relevant to his ability to practice medicine in any case.%0a%0a[1] https://news.nau.edu/kang-english-accents/#.YIzOS6lKgTU%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
